<h2>The Science of Cold Brew</h2>

<p>
  Cold brew coffee uses cold water (4–20°C) instead of hot water, extracting coffee compounds over a long period of 8–24 hours. The standard starting ratio is 1:8 (coffee to water), producing a concentrate that is diluted before serving.
</p>

<p>
  The most important characteristic of cold extraction is that <strong>the compounds extracted are fundamentally different from hot-water extraction</strong>. Chlorogenic acid derivatives — bitter compounds in coffee — break down and extract far more readily at high temperatures. At cold temperatures, these compounds dissolve much less, resulting in a smooth cup with suppressed acidity, pronounced sweetness, and a clean, round body. Volatile aromatic compounds also remain in solution rather than escaping as steam, giving cold brew a distinct aromatic depth.
</p>

<p>
  Multiple studies have confirmed that cold brew has a <strong>pH approximately 0.3–0.5 higher</strong> (less acidic) than hot-brewed coffee from the same beans. This is frequently cited as the reason cold brew is gentler on the stomach, though individual physiology and bean quality also play significant roles.
</p>

<p>
  Medium-dark to dark naturally processed beans are traditional choices for cold brew. However, light-roast specialty beans brewed cold can reveal a uniquely vibrant sweetness and fruit character that is difficult to achieve through hot extraction — the cold process selectively emphasizes different flavor compounds.
</p>

<h2>How to Make Cold Brew</h2>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Cold Brew Concentrate — Basic Recipe</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Coffee:</strong> 80g (coarse grind — French press coarseness or coarser)<br />
    <strong>Water:</strong> 640ml cold or room-temperature water (1:8 ratio, concentrate)<br />
    <strong>Temperature:</strong> Room temperature or refrigerator (4–20°C)<br />
    <strong>Steep time:</strong> 18–24 hours in the refrigerator (8–12 hours at room temperature)<br />
    <strong>Filter:</strong> Filter twice — first through a coarse filter to remove grounds, then through a fine paper or cloth filter to remove fines<br />
    <strong>Serve:</strong> Dilute concentrate 1:1 with water or milk<br /><br />
    Combine grounds and cold water in a jar or dedicated cold brew vessel. Stir gently to wet all the grounds. Cover and refrigerate. When done, filter in two passes into a clean storage container. Keeps refrigerated for up to 2 weeks.
  </p>
</div>

<p>
  Grind coarse. Medium or fine grinds will over-extract during the long steep, producing harsh bitterness and astringency. Coarse grinding also makes filtration far easier. A quality burr grinder producing uniform particles is one of the most important factors in cold brew quality.
</p>

<h2>Moka Pot (Macchinetta)</h2>

<p>
  The Moka Pot — or macchinetta — was invented in 1933 by Italian engineer Alfonso Bialetti. Its iconic octagonal aluminum design became so embedded in Italian culture that the Bialetti Moka Express is estimated to be present in 90% of Italian homes. Bialetti's son Renato expanded the company globally through aggressive marketing in the 1950s and 60s, making this arguably the most widely sold coffee brewing device in history.
</p>

<p>
  The mechanism is steam pressure driven. Water in the lower boiler chamber is heated until steam pressure builds to approximately <strong>1.5 bar</strong>. This pressure forces hot water upward through a bed of coffee grounds in the filter basket, and extracted coffee collects in the upper server chamber. This is significantly less pressure than an espresso machine (9 bar), so <strong>no crema forms</strong> — but the elevated pressure produces a more concentrated, full-bodied brew than drip coffee.
</p>

<p>
  It's important to understand: Moka pot coffee is <strong>not espresso</strong>. Espresso is defined by specific conditions (9+ bar, 25–30 seconds extraction time, fine grind). Moka coffee is its own category with distinct chemistry and flavor. However, it shares espresso's concentration and bold character, making it an excellent base for milk drinks when a machine is unavailable.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Moka Pot Recipe and Method</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Coffee:</strong> Fill the basket level (do not tamp or compress)<br />
    <strong>Water:</strong> Fill the lower boiler to just below the safety valve<br />
    <strong>Grind:</strong> Medium-fine (coarser than espresso, finer than drip)<br />
    <strong>Heat:</strong> Medium-low heat — high heat scorches the coffee and creates harsh flavors<br /><br />
    <strong>Steps:</strong> 1. Fill lower chamber with water 2. Insert basket, fill level with grounds 3. Screw chambers together firmly 4. Heat on medium-low 5. When coffee rises with a gurgling sound, reduce to low 6. Remove from heat when upper chamber is full; run cold water over the base to stop extraction
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Ibrik (Turkish Coffee / Cezve)</h2>

<p>
  The ibrik — also called cezve in Turkish — is one of the world's oldest coffee brewing implements. The tradition of Turkish coffee dates to the Ottoman Empire in the 15th–16th centuries and was inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage list in 2013. It remains the dominant brewing method across Turkey, the Middle East, the Balkans, and parts of Central Asia.
</p>

<p>
  The method is unlike any other. <strong>Extremely finely ground coffee</strong> (nearly powder consistency — finer than espresso) is combined with cold water and often sugar in the small long-handled pot (ibrik/cezve), then heated directly over a flame or hot sand. The mixture is brought nearly to a boil two or three times, allowing a thick foam to form. The foam is highly prized — some traditions decant a portion of the foam into each cup before pouring the liquid. Coffee grounds are not filtered; they settle to the bottom of the cup. <strong>You wait for them to settle, then drink.</strong>
</p>

<p>
  The flavor of Turkish coffee is intense: strong, slightly earthy bitterness balanced by sweetness (if sugar was added during brewing — not after), with a syrupy, almost velvety body from the fine grounds in suspension. Cardamom is commonly added in many regional traditions, adding aromatic complexity.
</p>

<p>
  The settled coffee grounds at the bottom of an inverted cup are used for <strong>fortune telling (tasseography)</strong> — a cultural practice that illustrates how deeply coffee is woven into the social and ritual fabric of the cultures that pioneered it.
</p>

